# ── SCOTTSBORO BOYS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
make(
  filename='/home/user/app/thread-scottsboro.html',
  acc=acc, acc_lt=acc_lt, hero_bg=hero_bg,
  kicker='Jim Crow Era · 1931 – 1950',
  title_html='The Scottsboro Boys:<br /><em>Nine Teenagers and the Trial That Exposed American Justice</em>',
  subtitle='Nine Black teenagers, ages 13–20, were falsely accused of rape on a freight train in Alabama in 1931. They were nearly lynched, tried in days, and sentenced to death. The case lasted 19 years, reached the Supreme Court twice, and became the most important civil rights legal case before Brown v. Board — and left most of the nine men destroyed.',
  meta_items=[('Era','Jim Crow Era'),('Dates','1931 – 1950'),('Ages','13–20 at time of arrest'),('Supreme Court','Two landmark decisions: Powell v. Alabama (1932), Norris v. Alabama (1935)')],
  central_arg='The Scottsboro case is the clearest single illustration of the Jim Crow justice system operating exactly as designed: nine Black teenagers facing all-white juries, inadequate counsel, mob pressure, and fabricated testimony, in a state where the outcome was predetermined. The two Supreme Court decisions it produced — establishing the right to counsel and prohibiting exclusion of Black people from juries — are among the most important in 20th-century civil rights law.',
  entries_html="""
<div class="entry-item" id="e1">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">1</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">March 25, 1931</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Freight Train: A Fight, a Fabrication, and Nine Arrests</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Paint Rock, Alabama</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>On March 25, 1931, a group of young Black men and two young white women — all riding illegally on a freight train through Alabama — get into a fight with a group of white men on the train. The white men are thrown off. When the train stops in <strong>Paint Rock, Alabama</strong>, a sheriff's posse arrests nine Black teenagers: <strong>Haywood Patterson</strong>, <strong>Clarence Norris</strong>, <strong>Charlie Weems</strong>, <strong>Olen Montgomery</strong>, <strong>Willie Roberson</strong>, <strong>Eugene Williams</strong>, <strong>Andy Wright</strong>, <strong>Roy Wright</strong>, and <strong>Ozie Powell</strong>. They range in age from 13 to 20. Most did not know each other before that day.</p>
    <p>The two white women — <strong>Victoria Price</strong> and <strong>Ruby Bates</strong> — initially claim to have been raped by the young men. (Ruby Bates later recants, testifying at a second trial that no rape occurred; Price never recants.) The accusation, in 1931 Alabama, carries an automatic death sentence. A <strong>mob of several thousand people</strong> surrounds the Scottsboro jail demanding immediate lynching. The National Guard is called in to prevent it. The defendants are tried within 10 days of their arrest.</p>
    <div class="entry-stats">
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">9</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Defendants, ages 13–20</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">10 days</div><div class="entry-stat__label">From arrest to conviction</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">2</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Supreme Court cases produced</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e2">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">2</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1931 – 1935</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Trials: All-White Juries, No Real Defense, Death Sentences in Hours</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Scottsboro, Alabama</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>The first trials are a travesty by any standard. Defense counsel is an elderly local lawyer so alcoholic that he is visibly impaired in court, and a Tennessee real estate attorney who had never tried a criminal case. The trials take one day each. The juries — all white, as Black people were systematically excluded from Alabama juries — deliberate for minutes. All nine defendants are convicted. Eight are sentenced to death. The ninth, <strong>Roy Wright</strong>, is 13 years old; the jury deadlocks on his sentence when some jurors want life imprisonment rather than death for a child.</p>
    <p>The <strong>International Labor Defense</strong> (ILD), affiliated with the Communist Party, takes up the case — making the Scottsboro Boys an international cause célèbre. The NAACP initially declines, fearing association with Communists. The ILD's involvement is controversial but effective: it raises money, hires skilled lawyers including <strong>Samuel Leibowitz</strong>, one of the best defense attorneys in the country, and organizes international pressure including protests in Europe and Latin America that embarrass the U.S. government.</p>
    <div class="pullquote"><p>"If you only convict these boys because they are Black and you are white, then God is not only against them — God is against you."</p><cite>— Samuel Leibowitz, closing argument, Scottsboro retrial, 1933</cite></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e3">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">3</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1932 – 1935</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">Two Supreme Court Victories That Changed American Law</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Washington, D.C.</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p><strong>Powell v. Alabama (1932)</strong>: The Supreme Court rules 7–2 that the defendants' right to adequate counsel under the 14th Amendment was violated. This is the first time the Supreme Court applies the 6th Amendment right to counsel to state criminal proceedings — a landmark ruling that establishes a constitutional requirement for adequate legal representation that still governs American criminal law today.</p>
    <p><strong>Norris v. Alabama (1935)</strong>: The Supreme Court rules unanimously that the systematic exclusion of Black people from Alabama's jury rolls violates the Equal Protection Clause. The Alabama officials had claimed no Black people were qualified to serve on juries — and had been caught falsifying jury rolls. The Court finds the exclusion unconstitutional, establishing a precedent against racially discriminatory jury selection that (imperfectly) governs jury law today.</p>
    <p>Despite two Supreme Court victories establishing their constitutional rights had been violated, the defendants are retried and reconvicted. Alabama refuses to acquit. <strong>Haywood Patterson</strong> is convicted four times. He eventually escapes to Michigan in 1948; the governor of Michigan refuses to extradite him. <strong>Clarence Norris</strong>, sentenced to death and repeatedly retried, is eventually paroled in 1946. He is the last of the Scottsboro Boys to be officially exonerated — by a pardon from the Governor of Alabama in 1976, 45 years after his arrest.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e4">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">4</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1931 – 1989</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Lives: What the System Did to Nine Teenagers</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Alabama prisons → North</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>The Scottsboro case produced two landmark Supreme Court victories and left most of its nine defendants destroyed. <strong>Willie Roberson</strong> had syphilis so advanced he could barely walk at the time of his arrest — physically incapable of assault. <strong>Olen Montgomery</strong> was nearly blind. Neither fact mattered at trial. Of the nine: most served prison terms ranging from 6 to 19 years. Several struggled with poverty, mental illness, and alcoholism after release. Haywood Patterson died of cancer in a Michigan prison in 1952, where he had been imprisoned on a manslaughter charge. <strong>Andy Wright</strong>, the last of the nine to be released, was paroled in 1950 — 19 years after his arrest on a freight train in Alabama.</p>
    <p>The final exoneration came in <strong>2013</strong> — 82 years after the arrests — when the Alabama Board of Pardons and Paroles posthumously pardoned the three who had never received individual pardons or exonerations: Haywood Patterson, Charlie Weems, and Eugene Williams. None of them lived to see it. The case is a perfect illustration of what the Jim Crow justice system was: not a system that occasionally made mistakes, but a system that <em>functioned correctly</em> from the perspective of those who designed it.</p>
  </div>
</div>
""",
  sidebar_html="""<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">The Nine</div><div class="sidebar-card__body"><strong>Haywood Patterson</strong> — convicted 4 times; escaped 1948; died 1952<br/><strong>Clarence Norris</strong> — paroled 1946; pardoned 1976<br/><strong>Charlie Weems</strong> — paroled 1943<br/><strong>Andy Wright</strong> — last released, 1950<br/><strong>Roy Wright</strong> — 13 years old at arrest; released 1937; died 1959<br/><strong>Olen Montgomery, Willie Roberson, Eugene Williams, Ozie Powell</strong> — released 1937</div></div>
<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">The Legal Legacy</div><div class="sidebar-card__body"><em>Powell v. Alabama</em> (1932) — Established right to adequate counsel in capital cases<br/><br/><em>Norris v. Alabama</em> (1935) — Prohibited systematic racial exclusion from juries<br/><br/>Both decisions are still cited in American criminal law today</div></div>""",
  cta_eyebrow='Nine Teenagers. Nineteen Years.',
  cta_title='Two Supreme Court victories. Most of the nine men were destroyed anyway.',
  cta_sub='The Scottsboro case shows what Jim Crow justice was: a system that produced the right legal outcomes when forced to by the Supreme Court, then reconvicted the defendants anyway. Winning in court was not the same as winning.',
  cta_href='thread-plessy.html', cta_text='Plessy v. Ferguson →', context_era='Jim Crow Era'
)
print("thread-scottsboro.html done")

# ── BOOKER T WASHINGTON ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
make(
  filename='/home/user/app/thread-booker-t-washington.html',
  acc=acc, acc_lt=acc_lt, hero_bg=hero_bg,
  kicker='Jim Crow Era · 1856 – 1915',
  title_html='Booker T. Washington:<br /><em>The Accommodation and Its Cost</em>',
  subtitle='He built Tuskegee Institute. He fed 10 million Black Southerners in a period of terror. He was also the most powerful Black man in America — and he used that power to suppress Black political dissent, block anti-lynching legislation, and tell white America that Black people would accept second-class citizenship. The debate he started with Du Bois is still unresolved.',
  meta_items=[('Era','Jim Crow Era'),('Born','April 5, 1856, Franklin County, Virginia (enslaved)'),('Died','November 14, 1915, Tuskegee, Alabama'),('Known for','Tuskegee Institute, Atlanta Compromise, Tuskegee Machine')],
  central_arg='Booker T. Washington is one of the most complicated figures in American history. He built an institution that educated thousands of Black people under conditions of violent oppression. He also made a deliberate strategic choice to accept disenfranchisement and segregation in exchange for white philanthropic support — a choice that has been debated as either pragmatic survival or catastrophic accommodation ever since. Understanding both sides of Washington is essential to understanding the full spectrum of Black political thought.',
  entries_html="""
<div class="entry-item" id="e1">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">1</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1856 – 1881</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">Born Enslaved, Built From Nothing: Washington's Rise</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Virginia → West Virginia → Hampton, Virginia</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>Booker Taliaferro Washington is born enslaved in April 1856 in Franklin County, Virginia. His father is almost certainly a white man — possibly his enslaver. After emancipation, his family moves to West Virginia where he works in salt furnaces and coal mines as a child. He teaches himself to read. At 16, he walks 500 miles to <strong>Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute</strong> in Virginia — arriving penniless, taking a job sweeping the entrance hall as his admission test, and staying to graduate in 1875.</p>
    <p>In 1881, the state of Alabama is looking for a principal for a new "colored" school in Tuskegee. They contact Hampton, expecting to receive a white man. Hampton recommends Washington. He arrives to find no buildings, no equipment, and almost no money — just a broken-down church and a hen house. He borrows money, buys land, and has students make their own bricks to build their own buildings. <strong>Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute</strong> is built, literally, by the labor of its students. It becomes one of the most important Black educational institutions in American history.</p>
    <div class="entry-stats">
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">1881</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Tuskegee Institute founded</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">1895</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Atlanta Compromise speech</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">1901</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Dines with President Roosevelt; Southern white backlash</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e2">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">2</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">September 18, 1895</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Atlanta Compromise: What Washington Offered and What It Cost</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Atlanta, Georgia</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>On September 18, 1895, Washington delivers the speech that defines his legacy — and divides Black America. At the Cotton States Exposition in Atlanta, before a largely white audience, he offers what becomes known as the <strong>Atlanta Compromise</strong>: Black people will accept social segregation and political disenfranchisement in exchange for economic opportunity and education. His most famous line: <em>"In all things that are purely social we can be as separate as the fingers, yet one as the hand in all things essential to mutual progress."</em></p>
    <p>White America — North and South — responds with thunderous approval. Northern industrialists like <strong>Andrew Carnegie</strong> and <strong>John D. Rockefeller</strong> begin pouring money into Tuskegee. Washington becomes the most powerful Black man in America, effectively controlling Black political appointments under Presidents Cleveland, McKinley, and Roosevelt. His network — the <strong>Tuskegee Machine</strong> — influenced Black newspapers, Black schools, and Black organizations across the country. Leaders who opposed his accommodationist line found their funding cut and their reputations attacked.</p>
    <div class="pullquote"><p>"Mr. Washington represents in Negro thought the old attitude of adjustment and submission. He practically accepts the alleged inferiority of the Negro race."</p><cite>— W.E.B. Du Bois, <em>The Souls of Black Folk</em>, 1903</cite></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e3">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">3</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1895 – 1915</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Secret Washington: The Man Who Fought Segregation in Private</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Tuskegee, New York, Washington D.C.</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>Here is the complication that makes Washington impossible to simply condemn: historians have documented that <strong>he secretly funded legal challenges to segregation</strong> while publicly accepting it. He provided anonymous financial support for lawsuits against Jim Crow railway cars, voter suppression, and peonage. He used intermediaries to hide his involvement from the white philanthropists whose support he needed. The man who told white audiences that Black people would accept separate but equal was simultaneously writing checks to lawyers challenging it.</p>
    <p>Washington's defenders argue this is pragmatism at its finest — working within the constraints of a violent white supremacist system to extract maximum gains for Black people. His critics, beginning with Du Bois, argue that his public accommodation gave white supremacy a legitimacy it would not otherwise have had, that his suppression of dissent through the Tuskegee Machine damaged Black political development, and that his framework — emphasizing industrial education over higher education, economic advancement over political rights — left Black America without the political tools to defend its economic gains when they were inevitably attacked.</p>
    <p>Both arguments are correct. Washington operated in conditions of extreme terror — Reconstruction had just been violently destroyed, lynching was epidemic, and overt resistance to white power typically meant death. His institution survived and educated thousands. His accommodation also provided cover for the construction of the Jim Crow system. This is the tension at the heart of his legacy.</p>
  </div>
</div>
""",
  sidebar_html="""<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">Washington vs. Du Bois</div><div class="sidebar-card__body"><strong>Washington:</strong> Industrial education, economic self-sufficiency, accept social separation, avoid confrontation with white power<br/><br/><strong>Du Bois:</strong> Liberal arts education, political rights, civil equality, direct confrontation with white supremacy<br/><br/>The debate they represent — accommodation vs. resistance, pragmatism vs. principle — runs through Black political thought from 1895 to the present.</div></div>
<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">Tuskegee's Legacy</div><div class="sidebar-card__body">George Washington Carver did his groundbreaking agricultural research at Tuskegee<br/><br/>The Tuskegee Airmen trained there<br/><br/>Tuskegee University continues today as one of the nation's leading HBCUs<br/><br/>The Tuskegee Syphilis Study — the most notorious medical ethics violation in U.S. history — was also conducted there</div></div>""",
  cta_eyebrow='Accommodation and Its Costs',
  cta_title='He built Tuskegee. He also told white America that Black people would accept second-class citizenship.',
  cta_sub='Washington\'s legacy is genuinely contested — not because the history is unclear but because the strategic question he answered is still unanswered: when faced with overwhelming violent power, do you accommodate or resist? Both choices have consequences.',
  cta_href='thread-dubois.html', cta_text='W.E.B. Du Bois →', context_era='Jim Crow Era'
)
print("thread-booker-t-washington.html done")
